column373:
10/Apr/2017 01:34 PM;andrewredmond;Hi

If you look at the initialise function of the com.norkom.base.business.util.PropertyManager which is the main property manager for the application it has the following logic that fits the 3 step approach that Richard mentions: (you can ignore the migration step as this should no longer be relevant)

public synchronized void initialize() throws IOException
    {
        if(initialLoad)
        {
            // read base_config.properties once initially
            loadPropertiesFromFileInitially();

            initialLoad = false;
        }

        if(!migrationPerformed)
        {
            // perform migration of properties from appliation.properties file
            migrateApplicationPropertiesFile();
        }

        // read system parameter table
        loadPropertiesFromDatabase();

        // read base_config.properties again in case any system properties are overridden
        loadPropertiesFromFile();
}

it looks like the com.norkom.base.web.util.WebPropertyManager class contains a bug in that it does not follow the same approach. Its not clear to me how this was missed during the performance improvements that were made previously.

It should be straightforward to apply the same logic to the WebPropertyManager or better yet refactor it to read all of its properties from the main property manager and no longer maintain its own list of properties. Similar refactoring was already performed on the com.norkom.common.util.PropertyManager class.

Ideally the application should be reading all properties from a single property manager but it would require a lot of refactoring to do this as multiple property managers were used iver the years by a large number of classes.

Lastly just to comment on the property file only being read if it's modified time has changed. The application keeps track of the last modified time of the file in a static variable. If you restart the application this variable is destroyed and therefore there is no last modified time stored to check against when the Property Manager is instantiated. This guarantees the file is read once after the database properties are loaded and it will only be read again thereafter if it is modified or until the application is restarted again.

Thanks

Andy

column369:
21/Feb/2017 03:19 PM;RHome;This the the method:

{code:java}
	public static boolean getPeriodReplacementChar (final String text, final int position)
	{
		//determine the replacament value
		//if period has 2 contiguous alpha numerics either before or after then replace by space
		//otherwise just remove period

		boolean bReplaceWithSpace = false;
		String wordPart;

		//get substring #.## around period position
		Matcher matcher = NormConstants.P1.matcher(text);
		if(matcher.find()){ //In case we have a match in the text using the pattern P1
			wordPart = matcher.group(0); //we retrieve the match
			if (NormConstants.P1.matcher(wordPart).matches())
			{
				bReplaceWithSpace = true;
			}
		}
		else
		{
			//get substring ##.# around period position
			matcher = NormConstants.P2.matcher(text);
			if(matcher.find()){ //In case we have a match in the text using the pattern P2
				wordPart = matcher.group(0); //we retrieve the match
				if (NormConstants.P2.matcher(wordPart).matches())
				{
					bReplaceWithSpace = true;
				}
			}
		}
		return bReplaceWithSpace;
	}
{code}

The method ignores the position parameter.

It also uses matcher.find() which scans the whole input rather than anchoring it around the current position (and will also be slow, especially as it is called for each period in the input).

It needs a different approach, I think. The REs allow for multiple successive periods, which is not a requirement I think and might actually be a worse result. The string a...b.text should probably be normalised to "a b text" and not "ab text".

I would just forget the REs and just check the characters before and after the current position directly, being careful not to fall of the beginning or end of the string.

