01/Feb/2018 09:44 AM;RHome;The original RBI bug concerned a custom transformer, but I believe the problem will occur with the standard NarrativeFieldTransformer as well (plus the potential to affect others in a simiar way).

The high-level cause was the decision to perform the message parsing to populate the data fields and the message parsing to populate the offset data for highlighting in two different methods. This means that any difference in the way the parsing is done is going to cause the logic to fail.

In the NarrativeFieldTransformer in the transform method (parsing to populate fields) we have this code:

{code:java}
	if( option.length() == 0 ) {
	    text = value;
	} else {
		// All other options
		int idx = value.indexOf("//");
		if( idx == -1 ) 
                {
                    text = value;
                }
                else
                {
    		    idx += 2;
    		    text = value.substring(idx);
                }
	}
{code}

So text is equal to the input if there is  no option. If there is an option it starts after '//' or if there is no '//' it is again just the input.

In the method buildCustomValuePositions to calculate the offsets, the parsing logic is as follows:

{code:java}
		int idx = value.indexOf("//");
		if( idx == -1 )
		{
		    startPosition = 0;
		    offset = value.length();
		}
		else
		{
		    startPosition = idx + 2;
		    offset = value.substring(startPosition).length();
		}
{code}

So here, no consideration is taken f the option. Only as to whether there is a '//' in the input or not. Potentially, there is a mismatch between the text popuated in the field and the offset calculated.

The problem is that for some reason, although transform receives option as a parameter, buildCustomValuePositions does not. So it is not possible to directly perform the same parsing anyway.

I realised I could make a hack and deduce what the logic in transform had done by comparsing the length of the original input and the length of the populated field and if they were the same I could conclude that the entire input had been used. 

But it general, I think this approach of separately parsing to populate the fields and to calculate the field offsets is doomed. It seems inevitable that someone is going to make a mistake unless the two bits of code are near identical, and in that case you might as well do it in one place.

To be taken into account is the fact that this code has other issues:
1. It isn't thread safe: the customValuePositionsMap map is shared between threads and can easily get corrupted.
2. It doesn't seem to understand multi-values well. There are places in the code (e.g., in the GenericSwiftMessageHandler where mult-values arrays and lists are received but the code just takes element zero and ignores the rest.

So I think all this highlighting code needs further reviewing and probably rewriting.

