Hi Alan

there is a fundamental issue with using float for the math.. float arithmetic is not precise..

This is an issue to take up with product I know.

But to illustrate behavior of the LevenshteinAbbreciationScorer when matching name and different number of initials. the problem case is 3 initials.

MOHAMMAD KARIM Abdullah Hamad vs MOHAMMAD K A H

float score = 0.0f;

float a = 1.0f; (exact match)

float b = 0.8f; (initial to word match)

If I have name + two initials I get

score+=a;
score+=b;
score+=b;

results in score = 2.6 and when dividing this by 3 (num of indexes) an alert score of 86.6666

If I have name + three initials I get

score+=a;
score+=b;
score+=b;
score+=b;

results in 3.3999999 instead of 3.4 and when dividing this by 4 (num of indexes) an alert score of 0.84999996 instead of 0.85. 

If I have name + four initials I get

score+=a;
score+=b;
score+=b;
score+=b;
score+=b;

results in score = 4.2 and when dividing this by 5 (num of indexes) an alert score of 84.

as 85% is a commonly used threshold and part of the ootb config, missing these alerts is NOT great... 



any suggestions how to fix this in this instance, but product really needs to review the use of float for the alert score calculations as when the precision works the other way 3.4000001, the result is above the threshold hence no material impact to alerting as such.

But i can imagine there are plenty other examples where simple addition of floats could result in fraction lower result and missed alerts.

