13/Jan/2020 03:12 PM;kmackenna1;Hi Trevor, Michal,

Re my first suggested fix earlier in this JIRA, there is another fix that does not involve changing table structures or the Change Risk workflow.

The idea behind this fix is as follows
{code:java}
We never want the link between the ASSIGNED_RISK_ID (risk level) and RISK_MODEL_ID (its originating model) to be broken.{code}
This can be accomplished in CDDScorePersister.handleResult by changing

*From*
{code:java}
            // Assignment logic
            if ("M".equals(oldScore.getSource()))  // was manually updated
            {
                score.setAssignedRiskId(oldScore.getAssignedRiskId());
		...
{code}
*To*
{code:java}
            // Assignment logic
            if ("M".equals(oldScore.getSource()))  // was manually updated
            {
                score.setAssignedRiskId(oldScore.getAssignedRiskId());
                // Maintain the link between the manually assigned risk level and the previous model
                score.setRiskModelId(oldScore.getRiskModelId()); {code}
All pre-existing and new JUnits pass under this modification. In particular, the oldLevel is now always correctly being found, as expected.

After searching for "RISK_MODEL_ID" across all files (*.java, *.sql, *.xml, etc.), it appears that no other part of the system, including UI, is impacted by this change, which suggests that the CDD_CUSTOMER_SCORE.RISK_MODEL_ID field is, indeed, dedicated to the use of manually assigned levels which would, in turn, render this fix benign.

(However, we would need a Services or UI person to confirm this, if possible).

Comments welcome!

Kieran

column386:
14/Jan/2020 04:07 AM;KOReilly;Thanks Kieran and Michal.

Logically, I like Michal's idea of storing the appropriate ASSIGNED_RISK_ID for the current model.  But I think this fix comes with a few questions which need to be answered:
* How do we determine the correct risk id in the new model (assumption is we would compare text on the description)
* What to do when there is no matching value in the new model? Do we remove the override? (I think we can clear this one with clients that they can't make major overhauls to the model without something like this happening and it can be managed)
* The problem currently only shows itself on the 2nd rescore after the model change, this is because on the first rescore when it is looking at the score history the model id is still correct for the assigned risk - therefore how do we know when the model has changed and that we need to change the assigned_risk_id to the new model?

Kieran's solution is definitely more simple, I had a quick look at the code and agree with him that it appears there is no need to pull calculated_risk_id from the model and therefore it is fine to use the model_id field for assigned_risk_id.  There are 2 outstanding questions for this one:
* How do we manage the fact that if a customer is scored at the same score value that they were overridden to they should have their override removed?  See code snippet - but basically calculated_risk_id and assigned_risk_id will never be equal if they are not from the same model
{code:java}
if ("M".equals(oldScore.getSource())) // was manually updated
 {
 score.setAssignedRiskId(oldScore.getAssignedRiskId());
 // Preserve risk level if parameter is true or if calculated risk level != assigned risk level
 if (preserveManualRisk || !score.getCalcRiskId().equals(score.getAssignedRiskId()))
 score.setSource("M");

 score.setEntity(oldScore.getEntity());
}
{code}

* If a customer has loaded a new model, it stands to reason they want to use the new model - but historically we are keeping them on the old model.  I imagine in most cases the model's changes are minor and might be to do with the scores required to reach that risk level, but just another question which requires thought.

So that is my 2 cents - we are happy either way, as long as the issue is resolved and Product are happy with the solution and it will be the way forward.  We are also very happy to test the change.

Thanks very much.

Kate

