                log.warn(this.riskDimension+": re-scoring but old Risk level ["+oldScore.getAssignedRiskId()+"] not found. Continuing as there wasn't oldLevel before.");

	...
{code}
*Change To*
{code:java}
        if (oldScore != null)
        {       
            oldLevel = loadRiskLevel(dbacces, oldScore);
            if (oldLevel == null)
                log.warn(this.riskDimension+": re-scoring but old Risk level ["+oldScore.getAssignedRiskId()+"] not found. Continuing as there wasn't oldLevel before.");

            if (oldLevel != null && oldLevel.getModelId() != this.curModel.getId()) {
            	/*
            	 * If a new model has been set to production, try to find the old manually-assigned level in
            	 * the new model and update the ASSIGNED_RISK_ID accordingly. If not found, just do as previously.
            	 */
            	for (RiskModelLevel curLevel : this.curModel.getLevels())
            	{
            		if (curLevel.getLevel().equalsIgnoreCase(oldLevel.getLevel()) &&
            			curLevel.getEntity().equalsIgnoreCase(oldLevel.getEntity()) &&
            			curLevel.getOrgUnit().getId() == oldLevel.getOrgUnit().getId())
            		{
            			// Found manually-assigned risk level in the current production model.
            			oldScore.setAssignedRiskId(curLevel.getId());
            			break;
            		}
            	}
            } {code}
The above changes represents the fix for the first/main issue and will ensure that the ASSIGNED_RISK_ID will be kept in sync with the current production model - if the old risk level name is also in present in the new model.

All pre-existing and new JUnits pass.

This design has the extra benefit of automatically updating any ASSIGNED_RISK_ID fields that have already become out-of-sync in the table.

For the secondary issue, where the old level is not found in the new model, we have 2 choices
 * Do nothing - things will function like they have until now, whenever a level or transition wasn't found.
 * Do something - for example, automatically revert to system scoring ('S') and the default calculated risk...?

As usual, comments welcome!

Thanks,

Kieran

