column74:
Method _characters_ in DefaultSwiftMXHandler calls method _normalize_, presumably to replace tabs by spaces and remove carriage returns and line feeds. However, method _normalize_ doesn’t actually do anything (unless the entire element is just whitespace). For each character, it calls method _valid_ to check if the character should be replaced (method _valid_ returns the character to use, either the original value or a replacement), but the return value is just discarded and the original character added to the “normalised” value.

Also, it seems the intention is to completely remove carriage returns and line feeds, which I think is an error because it would concatenate two words (one at the end of the line, the other at the start of the next line) into a single word. Such concatenations may cause unnecessary WLM matches and also suppress real matches. Carriage returns and line feeds should be replaced by spaces (or it should be configurable whether to remove them completely or replace them by spaces).

To allow proper control of text normalisation, the logic to normalise text should be moved from method _characters_ to method _endElement_. And it may be better to use String.replaceAll(“\\s+”, “ “).trim().

{code}
final char[][] replace = {
      {'\n', 0x00},
      {'\t', ' '},
      {'\r', 0x00}
   };

public void characters(char[] ch, int start, int length) throws SAXException {
   char[] normBuf = normalize(ch, start, length);
   // Rest of method removed for readability
   // as it's not relevant to the problem at hand
}

private char[] normalize(char buf[], int offset, int len)
{
   int numberOfBlankCharacters = 0;
   int indx =0;
   char[] norm = new char[len];  
   for (int i=0; i < len; i++){
      char c = buf[offset+i];
      if(c=='\n'||c=='\t'||c=='\r'||c==' ')
         numberOfBlankCharacters++;

      valid(c);
      norm[indx++] = c;
   }   
   if(numberOfBlankCharacters!=len)
      return norm;
   else
      return null;
}

private char valid(char c)
{
   // loop through all replacers
   for(int i=0; i<replace.length;i++)
      if(replace[i][0] == c)             // check if character must be replaced
         c = replace[i][1];       // replace character
   return c;
}
{code}

This code has been discovered in the version 6.1.2 and hasn't been changed since.

This can be easily fixed by updating the field formatter to a memo field formatter instead of the current text field formatter

i.e.
{code}
//FIX for normalization rule set Test screen
update section_fields 
SET FORMAT_TYPE_ID = (select ID from format_types where class_name = 'com.norkom.configurator.web.screens.fields.formatter.MemoFieldFormatter')
where ID = (select ID from section_fields where name = 'sys_norm_field_TestInput');
{code}

