Our client (Santander UK Retail) has recently enabled a housekeeping schedule which invokes the batch cleanup job class: _com.norkom.acquisition.business.scheduler.basic.BatchCleanupJob_

which executes the following queries in turn:


{code:sql}
DELETE FROM ACQ_BATCH_EVENT WHERE ACQ_BATCH_EVENT.EVENT_TIMESTAMP < ?
;

DELETE FROM ACQ_BATCH_PROCESS_PARAM WHERE BATCH_PROCESS_ID IN (
  SELECT ACQ_BATCH_PROCESS.BATCH_PROCESS_ID FROM ACQ_BATCH_PROCESS WHERE ACQ_BATCH_PROCESS.CREATED_TIMESTAMP < ? AND ACQ_BATCH_PROCESS.BATCH_PROCESS_ID NOT IN (
    SELECT ACQ_BATCH_EVENT.BATCH_PROCESS_ID FROM ACQ_BATCH_EVENT WHERE ACQ_BATCH_EVENT.BATCH_PROCESS_ID = ACQ_BATCH_PROCESS.BATCH_PROCESS_ID
  )
);

DELETE FROM ACQ_BATCH_PROCESS WHERE ACQ_BATCH_PROCESS.CREATED_TIMESTAMP < ? AND ACQ_BATCH_PROCESS.BATCH_PROCESS_ID NOT IN (
  SELECT ACQ_BATCH_EVENT.BATCH_PROCESS_ID FROM ACQ_BATCH_EVENT WHERE ACQ_BATCH_EVENT.BATCH_PROCESS_ID = ACQ_BATCH_PROCESS.BATCH_PROCESS_ID
);
{code}
 
The queries executed by this class are sufficient if removing delta of ~100s of records from <1mil in total when using the default cron schedule and age parameter.

However, if there is a backlog to cleanup (in this case present because the client is stress-testing an event where the server providing the HK functionality is not running for extended periods of time), then this is not performant and the query execution time will explode.

In our situation, we have > 2 weeks' worth of records in ACQ_BATCH_PROCSS (~2 million records), with HK attempting to clear >75% of these - extrapolation of the query suggested it would take several weeks to complete (killed after 4 days).

